Tech folks who teach things so rarely try to get to grips with Totally New Things, which is the experience a good chunk of their audience is having. 

I've tried several times to get into react-type JS front end stuff (I prefer back end work) and every single time one of these sorts of issues sets me back hours. Given I don't actually -have- to do this, but am just doing it as a hobby, I tend to drop it again a few of these sorts of scenarios in, having been thoroughly annoyed and frustrated by what looks like all the people in the know straight up hiding essential information for no good reason.

Not really. Just make sure you re-read this email every time you are about to write some tutorial for something. This feeling is so easy to lose and you'll 100% lose track of the kinds of things that were tripping you up. I know because I do the same thing when I talk about the stuff I know my shit about.

answers.text: This is my favorite email I've received from you thus far. In my previous role, I was a full time instructor at Hack Reactor, SF, and  was the second most senior person at work. I enjoyed the luxury of owning everything I did, and being perceived as in charge of all of my endeavors. I recently started working at Facebook. I applied via a staffing company, and thus am a contractor. I am perceived much differently. I'm called a noob. My "senior" engineer decided to teach me how to type on multiple lines at a time yesterday, by using cmd + shift + d. My environment is new, the languages are new, the projects are much different than what I'm used to. I'm working in a giant monolith, every task involves 5 new tools at once, and tools are named with arbitrary, unintuitive, stupid names, like "Scuba," which implies nothing when mentioned in passing. Worse, questions are encouraged, and then judged sharply. My team mates are annoyed if I request help. After three months, I'm tired of it. I've been allowing their immediate perception of me, coming from a bootcamp, not being a full-time employee, affect my own attitude and behaviors at work. I am acting submissive to the other engineers and project managers around me...for no reason at all. Because I'm new? This, is bullshit. I was never this way. The only accessible variable in this equation is my own behavior, and this email somehow made this very clear to me. Thank you. By the way, I love your work, even if I'm your most silent subscriber. I've recommended you to many friends. Please keep doing what you do. -Anthony Pecchillo
Not at the moment.
